NOTES_JAMES = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Doulos" (δοῦλος, Strong\'s G1401) means "bondservant" or "slave"—James identifies himself not by familial relation to Jesus but by servitude, a remarkable self-designation for the Lord\'s own brother. HISTORICAL: "The twelve tribes in the Dispersion" (diaspora, G1290) addresses Jewish believers scattered beyond Palestine, indicating an early date and Jewish-Christian audience. The greeting "chairein" (χαίρειν) is the standard Greek epistolary salutation, echoing the Jerusalem Council letter James presided over (Acts 15:23).',
        2: 'GREEK: "Peirasmos" (πειρασμός, G3986) can mean either "trial" (external testing) or "temptation" (internal enticement); here the context indicates outward trials. "Poikilos" (ποικίλος, G4164) means "many-colored, variegated, diverse"—trials come in manifold forms. THEOLOGICAL: Joy is not a feeling about suffering but a deliberate reckoning ("hēgēsasthe," aorist imperative) based on knowledge of what trials produce.',
        3: 'GREEK: "Dokimion" (δοκίμιον, G1383) refers to the "means of testing" or "proving," used of assaying metals for purity. Compare 1 Pet 1:7 where the same word describes faith tested by fire. "Hypomonē" (ὑπομονή, G5281) is not passive patience but active, steadfast endurance under pressure.',
        5: 'GREEK: "Haplōs" (ἁπλῶς, G574) means "generously, simply, without reservation"—it is a hapax legomenon in the NT. "Oneidizo" (ὀνειδίζω, G3679) means "to reproach, upbraid"—God gives without shaming the asker. THEOLOGICAL: God\'s character as the generous giver stands in contrast to double-minded human asking (vv. 6-8), establishing the theological foundation for prayer throughout the epistle.',
        8: 'GREEK: "Dipsychos" (δίψυχος, G1374) literally "double-souled," is a word found only in James in the NT (here and 4:8) and nowhere in prior Greek literature, making it likely a Jamesian coinage. "Akatastatos" (ἀκατάστατος, G182) means "unstable, restless"—the double-minded man is characterized by fundamental instability in every path he walks.',
        12: 'GREEK: "Stephanos tēs zōēs" (στέφανος τῆς ζωῆς)—the "crown of life" is a genitive of apposition: the crown which is life itself. "Stephanos" (G4735) refers to the victor\'s wreath, not the royal diadem (diadēma). TYPOLOGY: The crown of life promised to those who endure trials echoes Rev 2:10 and reflects the eschatological reward motif found throughout Second Temple Jewish literature. THEOLOGICAL: The promise is specifically to "those who love Him"—endurance is framed as an expression of covenant love for God.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: James makes a critical distinction between "peirasmos" as trial (v. 2) and "peirazo" as temptation to evil. God tests but never tempts. "Apeirastos" (ἀπείραστος, G551) is another rare term, meaning either "unable to be tempted" or "inexperienced in evil"—both senses reinforce God\'s absolute separation from moral evil. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This passage implicitly rejects any theology that attributes moral evil to the divine realm; evil originates in creaturely desire, not in the heavenly council.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: James presents a birth-and-death metaphor for the progression of sin: desire conceives (syllabousa, a term used for pregnancy), gives birth (tiktei) to sin, and sin when fully grown brings forth (apokyei) death. This echoes the Genesis 3 pattern where desire led to transgression and transgression to death (Gen 2:17; Rom 5:12). TYPOLOGY: The sequence inverts the life-giving pattern of v. 18, where God\'s will "brings forth" (apokyeō, same verb) life through the word of truth.',
        17: 'GREEK: "Dosis" (δόσις, G1394) emphasizes the act of giving; "dōrēma" (δώρημα, G1434) emphasizes the gift itself—James uses both to express the fullness of divine generosity. "Parallagē" (παραλλαγή, G3883) is a hapax legomenon meaning "variation" or "change," and "aposkiasma" (ἀποσκίασμα, G644) is also a hapax meaning "shadow cast by turning"—both are astronomical terms. DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Father of lights" (patēr tōn phōtōn) designates God as Creator of the celestial luminaries (Gen 1:14-18), and unlike the heavenly bodies which shift and cast shadows, He is utterly unchanging.',
        18: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Boulētheis" (βουληθείς)—"having willed," emphasizes the sovereign deliberation of God in bringing forth believers. "Apokyeō" (ἀποκυέω, G616) "brought forth" uses birth language, contrasting with v. 15 where desire "brings forth" death. TYPOLOGY: "Firstfruits" (aparchē, G536) draws on the OT offering of the first portion of harvest to God (Lev 23:10); believers are the inaugural portion of a renewed creation, anticipating the full harvest of new creation (Rom 8:19-23).',
        21: 'GREEK: "Emphytos" (ἔμφυτος, G1721) means "implanted" or "innate"—the word that has been engrafted into the believer, not merely heard externally. "Rhyparia" (ῥυπαρία, G4507) is a hapax legomenon meaning "moral filth." THEOLOGICAL: The implanted word is declared "able to save your souls" (psychas)—James affirms the saving power of the gospel word while simultaneously demanding that reception of it be accompanied by moral transformation.',
        25: 'GREEK: "Parakyptō" (παρακύπτω, G3879) means "to stoop down and look intently into," suggesting careful, sustained examination—the same verb used of Peter and John peering into the empty tomb (John 20:5, 11). "Nomon teleion ton tēs eleutherias"—"the perfect law, that of liberty"—identifies Torah as fulfilled and perfected in Christ, a law that liberates rather than enslaves (Gal 5:1). THEOLOGICAL: The one who perseveres in this law becomes not merely a hearer but a "doer of the work," and the blessing is located in the doing itself.',
        27: 'GREEK: "Thrēskeia" (θρησκεία, G2356) refers to the outward expression of worship and religious observance—James redefines it in ethical terms. "Aspilon" (ἄσπιλον, G784) means "without spot, unstained." THEOLOGICAL: Pure religion before God is defined not by ritual but by two actions: care for the most vulnerable (orphans and widows, echoing Deut 10:18; Ps 68:5; Isa 1:17) and personal holiness in separation from worldly corruption. This verse programmatically introduces the social ethics that dominate chapters 2-5.',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Partiality" (prosōpolēmpsíais, cf. Strong\'s G4382) is a compound from prosōpon ("face") and lambánō ("to receive")—literally "face-receiving," i.e., judging by outward appearance. This is a rare noun form found almost exclusively in biblical and early Christian literature. THEOLOGICAL: James links partiality directly to a violation of authentic faith in Christ, whom he calls "our Lord Jesus Christ, the Lord of glory" (tēs doxēs)—a genitive of quality or apposition identifying Christ Himself as the Glory, echoing the divine kavod/shekinah presence of God (cf. 1 Cor 2:8; Ex 40:34).',
        4: 'GREEK: "Made distinctions" (diekríthēte, G1252) can mean "to be divided" or "to waver," suggesting internal division and double-mindedness. "Evil reasonings" (dialogismōn ponērōn) recalls Jesus\' warnings about what proceeds from the heart (Mark 7:21). THEOLOGICAL: Partiality reveals corrupted judgment; believers have set themselves up as judges operating by worldly, demonic criteria rather than by the wisdom from above (Jas 3:15-17).',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: God\'s election of the poor inverts worldly values. "Rich in faith" and "heirs of the kingdom" echo Jesus\' Beatitudes (Matt 5:3; Luke 6:20). The kingdom is promised specifically to those who love God, echoing the Shema tradition (Deut 6:5) and Paul\'s language in 1 Cor 2:9 and Rom 8:28. TYPOLOGY: The poor as God\'s chosen inheritors recalls Israel\'s own identity as a small, enslaved people whom God chose—not for their power but by His sovereign grace (Deut 7:7-8).',
        8: 'GREEK: "Royal law" (nómon basilikón, G937) may mean the law belonging to the King (Christ) or the law that governs all other laws—the supreme law. TYPOLOGY: The quotation is from Lev 19:18 (LXX), which Christ Himself identified as the second greatest commandment (Matt 22:39). James thus identifies the Torah\'s love command as the reigning principle of the new covenant community under King Jesus.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: James articulates the unity and indivisibility of God\'s law. To break one commandment is to violate the whole, because the law reflects the singular will of one Lawgiver (v.11). This does not teach salvation by perfect law-keeping but rather exposes the impossibility of partial obedience as a basis for self-righteousness. The logic drives the hearer toward dependence on mercy (v.13).',
        13: 'GREEK: "Without mercy" (anéleos, G448) is a rare adjective—a hapax legomenon in the NT. "Triumphs over" (katakaucháomai, G2620) means to boast against or exult over, depicting mercy as victorious over judgment in an almost personified contest. THEOLOGICAL: This verse is the theological hinge of the chapter: God\'s mercy, shown through merciful living, overrides condemnation. It connects backward to the partiality discussion and forward to the faith-and-works argument, grounding both in the character of God Himself.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: This begins the famous faith-and-works discourse (vv.14-26). James does not contradict Paul (Rom 3:28) but addresses a different problem: a dead, merely verbal confession devoid of obedient action. The rhetorical question expects a negative answer in Greek (mē dýnatai)—"that faith cannot save him, can it?" The article hē pístis ("the faith") points to this particular kind of faith—the empty, workless kind just described.',
        19: 'GREEK: "Shudder" (phríssousin, G5425) is a hapax legomenon in the NT, describing a visceral, horrified trembling. THEOLOGICAL: The Shema confession "God is one" (Deut 6:4) is affirmed as correct belief, yet James devastatingly notes that demons share this orthodox theology. Mere intellectual assent to true doctrine, even the most foundational confession of Israel, does not constitute saving faith. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The demons (daimónia) are portrayed as spiritual beings who possess accurate theological knowledge of God\'s oneness yet remain in rebellious terror before Him—knowledge without allegiance.',
        21: 'TYPOLOGY: The binding of Isaac (the Aqedah, Gen 22:1-19) is the supreme OT test of faith-in-action. Abraham\'s willingness to offer his son demonstrated the reality of the faith credited to him in Gen 15:6. James reads Genesis narratively: the declaration of righteousness in Gen 15 was vindicated and brought to completion by the obedient act in Gen 22. THEOLOGICAL: "Justified by works" (ex érgōn edikaióthē) here means "shown to be righteous" or "vindicated"—the demonstrative, evidentiary sense of dikaióō, complementing Paul\'s forensic-declarative usage (Rom 4:2-3).',
        23: 'GREEK: "Was fulfilled" (eplērōthē, G4137) indicates that the Scripture reached its fullest expression—Gen 15:6 was not merely a past event but an ongoing reality brought to completion through Abraham\'s obedient life. "Friend of God" (phílos theoû) draws on 2 Chr 20:7 and Isa 41:8 (LXX), a unique covenantal title. TYPOLOGY: Abraham\'s faith-and-works unity foreshadows the believer\'s union with Christ, in whom faith is always active through love (Gal 5:6).',
        25: 'HISTORICAL: Rahab the harlot (Josh 2:1-21; 6:22-25) was a Canaanite woman—a Gentile outsider of the lowest social standing—whose faith was demonstrated by the concrete act of receiving Israel\'s spies and sending them out safely. TYPOLOGY: James deliberately pairs Abraham (the patriarch of Israel, male, righteous) with Rahab (a Gentile, female, harlot) to show that justifying faith expressed in works transcends every social and ethnic boundary. Both appear in Christ\'s genealogy (Matt 1:2, 5). GREEK: "Messengers" (aggélous, G32) here refers to human messengers/spies, the basic meaning of the word before its specialized use for heavenly beings.',
        26: 'THEOLOGICAL: The body-spirit analogy is the conclusive summary. Just as a body without spirit (pneúmatos) is a corpse, faith without works is spiritually dead—not merely deficient but lifeless. This is not a works-salvation argument but an insistence that genuine, living faith necessarily produces obedient action, as breath animates the body. STRUCTURE: This verse forms an inclusio with v.17, bracketing the entire argument: faith without works is dead (v.17), demonstrated by examples (vv.18-25), and restated with finality (v.26).',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'GREEK: "διδάσκαλοι" (didaskaloi, Strong\'s G1320) denotes teachers or instructors, a role of high authority in the early assembly. "κρίμα" (krima, G2917) here means judgment or verdict, not merely criticism — teachers face stricter divine evaluation because their words shape the faith of others. THEOLOGICAL: James writes as one who includes himself ("we shall receive"), indicating apostolic humility before the judgment seat of Christ (2 Cor 5:10).',
        2: 'GREEK: "πταίομεν" (ptaiomen, G4417) means to stumble or trip, used metaphorically for moral failure. "χαλιναγωγῆσαι" (chalinagōgēsai, G5468) means to lead with a bridle, a vivid compound word (chalinos + agō) unique to James in the NT (also Jas 1:26). "τέλειος" (teleios, G5046) signifies completeness or maturity, not sinless perfection.',
        6: 'GREEK: "τὸν τροχὸν τῆς γενέσεως" (ton trochon tēs geneseōs) is a difficult phrase, literally "the wheel of origin/birth." Some see Orphic or Stoic background, but in context it likely means the entire course of human existence from birth onward. "γεέννης" (geennēs, G1067) refers to Gehenna, the Valley of Hinnom (Ge-Hinnom), associated with divine judgment and destructive fire (Matt 5:22; Mark 9:43). THEOLOGICAL: The tongue\'s destructive power is portrayed as having its ultimate source in Gehenna itself — demonic instigation behind human speech that destroys.',
        8: 'GREEK: "ἀκατάστατον" (akatastaton, G182) means unstable or restless, the same root as "ἀκαταστασία" (disorder) in v.16. "θανατηφόρου" (thanatēphorou, G2287) is a NT hapax legomenon, a compound of "thanatos" (death) + "pherō" (to bear), meaning death-carrying or death-bearing. The imagery evokes the deadly serpent, recalling Genesis 3 and the deception wrought by the tongue of the ancient serpent.',
        9: 'GREEK: "κύριον" (kyrion, G2962) here refers to the Lord, likely God the Father in view of "and Father" following. "ὁμοίωσιν" (homoiōsin, G3669) echoes the LXX of Genesis 1:26 ("κατὰ ὁμοίωσιν"), where humanity is made according to the likeness of God. TYPOLOGY: James grounds the dignity of every human being in the imago Dei from creation — to curse a person made in God\'s likeness is to assault the image of the Creator Himself. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The "likeness of God" language connects humanity to the divine realm; humans bear the image of the Most High, set as His representatives on earth (Ps 8:5-6; Gen 1:26-27).',
        12: 'TYPOLOGY: The fig tree imagery recalls Jesus\'s cursing of the barren fig tree (Matt 21:19; Mark 11:13-14), a symbol of Israel\'s fruitlessness. James argues from nature that a single source cannot produce contradictory fruit — a principle rooted in Jesus\'s own teaching (Matt 7:16-18). The salt and sweet water illustration may evoke the bitter waters of Marah made sweet by God (Exod 15:23-25).',
        15: 'GREEK: "ἐπίγειος" (epigeios, G1919) means earthly, upon the earth — contrasted with "from above" (ἄνωθεν). "ψυχική" (psychikē, G5591) derives from "psychē" (soul) and denotes the merely natural or soulish, that which operates apart from the Spirit (cf. 1 Cor 2:14; Jude 19). "δαιμονιώδης" (daimoniōdēs, G1141) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning demon-like or demonic in character. THEOLOGICAL: James presents a descending triad — earthly, natural, demonic — showing that wisdom not from God degenerates toward the realm of hostile spiritual powers.',
        17: 'GREEK: "εὐπειθής" (eupeithēs, G2138) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning easily persuaded or compliant, from "eu" (well) + "peithō" (to persuade). "ἀδιάκριτος" (adiakritos, G87) is also a NT hapax, meaning without partiality or without wavering. THEOLOGICAL: The seven attributes following "pure" may echo the sevenfold Spirit of God (Isa 11:2). This heavenly wisdom is the character of God Himself manifest in believers — the same wisdom personified in Proverbs 8 and ultimately embodied in Christ (1 Cor 1:30; Col 2:3).',
        18: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse forms the conclusion to the entire discourse on wisdom. "Fruit of righteousness" echoes Proverbs 11:30 and Philippians 1:11. The passive "is sown" suggests divine agency — God produces righteousness through those who cultivate peace. TYPOLOGY: The peacemakers here correspond to those Jesus declared blessed (Matt 5:9), who are called "sons of God" — those whose character reflects the heavenly wisdom described in v.17.',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Wars" (πόλεμοι, polemoi, Strong\'s G4171) denotes large-scale conflicts, while "fightings" (μάχαι, machai, G3163) indicates quarrels or disputes. "Pleasures" (ἡδονῶν, hēdonōn, G2237) is the root of English "hedonism," here personified as soldiers waging campaign-style war (στρατευομένων, strateuomenōn) within one\'s own members. James echoes Paul\'s inner-war language (Rom 7:23).',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Adulteresses" (μοιχαλίδες, moichalides) employs the OT prophetic metaphor of spiritual adultery — Israel\'s unfaithfulness to YHWH as covenant-spouse (Hos 2:2; Jer 3:6-10; Ezek 16). James applies this covenantal imagery directly to the messianic community. Friendship (φιλία, philia) with the world-system constitutes a rival allegiance incompatible with loyalty to God, placing the worldly believer in the position of covenant-breaker.',
        5: 'GREEK: This verse is notoriously difficult to interpret. "The Spirit which He caused to dwell" (τὸ πνεῦμα ὃ κατῴκισεν, to pneuma ho katōkisen) may refer to the Holy Spirit whom God placed in believers, or the human spirit God implanted. "Yearns with jealousy" (πρὸς φθόνον ἐπιποθεῖ, pros phthonon epipothei) — ἐπιποθέω (G1971) means to long for intensely. The exact OT quotation James references remains unidentified, possibly a free rendering of Exod 20:5 or Deut 32:10-12. DIVINE_COUNCIL: God\'s jealousy for His people reflects His exclusive covenantal claim over those in whom His Spirit dwells.',
        6: 'TYPOLOGY: The quotation is from Prov 3:34 (LXX), also cited in 1 Pet 5:5. The pattern of divine resistance to the proud and favor toward the humble is a consistent scriptural principle (Ps 138:6; Isa 57:15; Luke 1:52). "Greater grace" (μείζονα χάριν) indicates that God\'s gracious provision exceeds the jealous longing of verse 5 — grace triumphs over the downward pull of worldly desire.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The imperative "submit" (ὑποτάγητε, hypotagēte, G5293, aorist passive) denotes placing oneself under God\'s authority — a military term for ranking under a commander. "Resist" (ἀντίστητε, antistēte, G436, aorist active) the devil (τῷ διαβόλῳ, tō diabolō, "the slanderer") carries the promise of his flight. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The devil is presented as a hostile spiritual being whose power is limited; he must flee when confronted by a believer aligned under God\'s sovereign authority (cf. Eph 6:11-13; 1 Pet 5:8-9).',
        8: 'TYPOLOGY: "Cleanse your hands...purify your hearts" echoes priestly purification language (Exod 30:19-21; Lev 16:30) and Ps 24:3-4 — "clean hands and a pure heart" as the requirement for ascending to the Lord\'s holy place. "Double-minded" (δίψυχοι, dipsychoi, G1374) is a word found only in James in the NT (also Jas 1:8), describing the divided loyalty condemned in verse 4.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Humble yourselves before the Lord" (ταπεινώθητε ἐνώπιον κυρίου) echoes the consistent biblical pattern that self-abasement before God precedes divine exaltation (1 Pet 5:6; Matt 23:12; Luke 14:11; Luke 18:14). The passive-voice promise "He will exalt you" (ὑψώσει ὑμᾶς) places the timing and manner entirely in God\'s sovereign hands.',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: "One Lawgiver and Judge" (εἷς νομοθέτης καὶ κριτής) — νομοθέτης (nomothetēs, G3550) is a NT hapax legomenon, appearing only here. James affirms the singular divine prerogative over both law-giving and judgment, the power "to save and to destroy" (σῶσαι καὶ ἀπολέσαι). This echoes Deut 32:39 and Isa 33:22, consolidating legislative and judicial authority in God alone, and thus rebuking presumptuous human judgment of one\'s neighbor.',
        14: 'GREEK: "Vapor" (ἀτμίς, atmis, G822) occurs only here and in Acts 2:19 in the NT. The imagery of human transience as mist or breath echoes Ps 39:5-6, Ps 144:4, and Eccl 6:12. "Appears for a little while and then vanishes" (πρὸς ὀλίγον φαινομένη ἔπειτα καὶ ἀφανιζομένη) — the participles frame life as a brief manifestation that dissolves, underscoring radical dependence on God\'s sovereign will (v.15).',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse functions as a concluding aphorism with universal application beyond its immediate context. It defines sin not merely as active transgression but as omission — knowing the good (καλόν, kalon) and failing to do it. This "sin of omission" principle has broad ethical implications and connects to Jesus\'s parable teachings (Luke 12:47-48). The dative αὐτῷ ("to him") makes the judgment intensely personal.',
    },
    5: {
        3: 'GREEK: κατίωται (katioōtai, from katióō) means "has become corroded/rusted" — a perfect passive indicating an existing state of decay. The verb is rare in biblical Greek. THEOLOGICAL: The irony is devastating: they stored up treasure (ἐθησαυρίσατε, ethēsaurisate) but what they stored is evidence for their own judgment "in the last days" (ἐν ἐσχάταις ἡμέραις), echoing Jesus\' teaching on true treasure (Matt 6:19-20).',
        4: 'GREEK: Κυρίου Σαβαώθ (Kyriou Sabaōth) — "Lord of Sabaoth" (i.e., Lord of Hosts/Armies), a direct transliteration from Hebrew צְבָאוֹת (tsevaʾot), preserved from the LXX of Isaiah 5:9. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This title evokes God as the commander of the heavenly armies, the cosmic sovereign who hears the oppressed. James deliberately invokes the most majestic OT divine-council title to heighten the terror of judgment against exploitative rich. TYPOLOGY: Echoes Deuteronomy 24:14-15 and Leviticus 19:13 — withholding wages was covenant violation crying to God.',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: τὸν δίκαιον (ton dikaion, "the righteous one") is singular, possibly referring both to the generic righteous poor person and typologically to Christ Himself — the Righteous One (Acts 3:14, 7:52) who did not resist His murderers (Isa 53:7). GREEK: οὐκ ἀντιτάσσεται (ouk antitassetai) — present middle: "he does not set himself against you," evoking the non-resistance of the innocent.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: ἡ παρουσία τοῦ κυρίου ἤγγικεν (hē parousia tou kyriou ēngiken) — "the coming of the Lord has drawn near." The perfect tense ἤγγικεν indicates a completed approach with ongoing relevance — the Lord\'s return is perpetually imminent. This is the same language used by Jesus in Mark 1:15 regarding the kingdom. GREEK: στηρίξατε (stērixate, aorist imperative of stērizō, Strong\'s G4741) — "establish firmly," used of resolute, unwavering commitment.',
        11: 'TYPOLOGY: Job is cited as the supreme OT example of endurance under suffering without understanding. τὸ τέλος κυρίου (to telos kyriou) — "the purpose/outcome of the Lord" — refers to how God brought Job\'s trial to a redemptive conclusion (Job 42:10-17). GREEK: πολύσπλαγχνος (polysplanchnos, Strong\'s G4184) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "very compassionate" or "full of tender mercy," compounding πολύς (much) + σπλάγχνον (inward parts/bowels of compassion). This rare word emphasizes the superabundance of divine mercy.',
        14: 'HISTORICAL: Anointing with oil (ἐλαίῳ, elaiō) in the ancient world served both medicinal (Luke 10:34) and sacramental purposes. The combination of physical care and prayer reflects the holistic Jewish understanding of healing. GREEK: πρεσβυτέρους τῆς ἐκκλησίας (presbyterous tēs ekklēsias) — "elders of the assembly" — indicates established leadership structures in the early Jewish-Christian communities. The term ekklēsia here carries its Septuagintal sense of the gathered covenant people.',
        16: 'GREEK: ἐνεργουμένη (energoumenē) is a present middle/passive participle of ἐνεργέω (energeō, Strong\'s G1754). If middle: "the prayer of a righteous one, being effectually at work, avails much." If passive: "being empowered/energized [by the Spirit]." The ambiguity may be intentional — righteous prayer is both humanly earnest and divinely empowered. THEOLOGICAL: The linkage of confession, intercession, and healing reflects the covenant community as a place of mutual restoration.',
        17: 'GREEK: προσευχῇ προσηύξατο (proseuchē prosēuxato) — a Hebraism using the cognate dative construction (infinitive absolute pattern), literally "he prayed with prayer," meaning "he prayed earnestly/fervently." TYPOLOGY: Elijah as a man ὁμοιοπαθής (homoiopathēs, "of like nature/suffering") demystifies prophetic power — extraordinary results come not from extraordinary persons but from extraordinary faith directed toward a faithful God (1 Kings 17:1; 18:42-45).',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: καλύψει πλῆθος ἁμαρτιῶν (kalypsei plēthos hamartiōn) — "shall cover a multitude of sins" — echoes Proverbs 10:12 (LXX) and 1 Peter 4:8. The covering of sins through restorative love within the community reflects the atoning work of Christ applied in the fellowship of believers. GREEK: ψυχὴν αὐτοῦ (psychēn autou) — "his soul" — the antecedent of αὐτοῦ is debated: it may refer to the soul of the sinner being rescued, or to the soul of the one who restores him. The former reading fits the immediate context of saving from spiritual death.',
    },
}